Anonymous Sat 10 Dec 2022 12:40:57 No.52935513 Report
Quoted By:
>>52934866
Unless you're experienced at doing it, don't. But at the end, I'll tell you how to start learning the skill.
My workflow usually involves 2-3 projects at a time. It is very rare that two of them are in the same stage of writing, especially first drafts, so it is easy for me to edit one and then swap over to writing.
But the foundation level skill you need to manage this is consistency. Set aside time and write. Your instincts on how to build scenes and beats come from very regular work.
Give yourself a set time each day for the less advanced project. Set a timer. When it goes off, you're done with be lesser project and swap to the other.
Now if your reason for wanting a second project is writer's block on the first project, you'll find it easier to get something out. For me, this is a great time to look at structure because I'm mentally warmed up. The day's bullshit is done, so thinking objectively is a touch easier.

String together weeks and months of workmanlike sessions, and you eventually finish projects.

It was an anime from Studio Bones from around 2004 called "Wolf's Rain." As far as I could tell it was not so much a coherent story as a character study about four magical wolf guys who can turn back and forth into human forms. The setting makes little sense--it's the far future, there's been some kind of unexplained and unexamined ecological apocalypse and human think wolves are extinct, but the wolves are really magically disguised walking among them. And it's the far future but the cars and the clothes and cityscapes look like it's 1970. And the wolves are on some kind of quest for a magical plot coupon that they think will reset the world and restore Eden. It didn't make very much sense. And episode to episode it was just these four dudes wandering around arguing and yelling at each other and not quite coming to blows. This specific character was named Blue. She was a minor supporting character in a secondary plot line about a grizzled old hunter who hates wolves--his rifle is this bizarre mechanical chimera that looks like something from an alternate universe Victorian Era, a lever action rifle with a revolver cylinder. Blue eventually becomes a love interest of one of the wolf dudes. It's gorgeously animated but nothing about it was very memorable other than her, and she didn't get much screen time. After a couple of episodes nothing about it made me desire to watch any more of it.
